Not all specimens have continuously straight-sided shells: BU 4370 is straight-sided for the first 11 annulations (∼ 
15 mm
) before changing growth direction (see 
Fig. 2F
). The shell is then straight-sided again for the rest of its length. 
Paratype
BMNH A846 (
Fig. 2H
) is very similar, showing a distinct change in growth direction after the 12th annulation, and with the annulations becoming difficult to identify in the apertural region. 
Paratype
BMNH A845 (
Fig. 2D, I
), in contrast, has a distinctly curved apical shell region before becoming straight-sided in the mid-region and towards the aperture. It becomes expanded and extremely irregular close to the aperture (see 
Fig. 2D
).

The apertural shell region is well preserved in 
paratype
BU 4371 (
Fig. 2J
) and has a morphology not seen in other specimens: after consistently increasing in diameter up to the annulation closest to the aperture, the shell then begins to close again, such that the aperture is narrower in diameter (∼ 
11 mm
) than the final annulation (∼ 
13 mm
). The origin and development of this apertural constriction is discussed below.
